INSERT INTO public.quiz_questions (level_id, topic_tag, question, options, correct_index, explanation)
VALUES
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A PE firm is conducting commercial due diligence on a €400M industrial target. What is the primary purpose of CDD?', '["To verify financial statements only","To validate the investment thesis — market attractiveness, competitive position, growth prospects, customer relationships — through independent analysis rather than accepting management''s view","To negotiate price","To structure the deal"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Commercial DD purpose: (1) Validate investment thesis independently; (2) Assess market attractiveness (size, growth, structure); (3) Evaluate competitive position (moats, share, differentiation); (4) Analyse customer dynamics (concentration, retention, satisfaction); (5) Validate growth assumptions (realistic, drivers, sustainability); (6) Identify risks (disruption, cyclicality, regulation). CDD is conducted by specialist consultants (Bain, McKinsey, L.E.K., OC&C, BCG) providing independent view. Complements: Financial DD (validates earnings), Legal DD (contracts, litigation), Operational DD (processes). CDD forms critical input to IC decision — often the difference between doing the deal and walking away.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team is evaluating market size for a specialised industrial services market. What approaches are typically used?', '["Only published industry reports","Multiple approaches: (1) Top-down (industry reports, market research); (2) Bottom-up (customer demand analysis); (3) Supply-side (competitor revenue aggregation); (4) Triangulation across methods; sophisticated analysis uses multiple approaches","Random estimation","Only competitor data"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Market sizing approaches: (1) Top-down: Industry reports (Euromonitor, IBISWorld, Statista), government data, trade associations; (2) Bottom-up: Analyse customer spending patterns, interview customers, sum from demand side; (3) Supply-side: Aggregate competitor revenues, capacity analysis; (4) Triangulation: Compare all three approaches for consistency. Example: specialised industrial services market: (1) Top-down: €15B global market per industry report; (2) Bottom-up: €12-18B based on customer interviews and spending analysis; (3) Supply-side: €13-17B based on top 20 competitors; (4) Triangulated estimate: €14-16B. Best CDD uses multiple approaches with explicit methodology. Single-source estimates often biased or outdated.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies that the target''s market is growing at 12%, while GDP grows at 2.5%. What does this suggest?', '["Growth is always sustainable","Fast growth exceeds GDP significantly, suggesting: (1) Structural growth drivers (demographics, technology, regulation); (2) Market penetration increasing; (3) Value migration; (4) Category expansion; but: (1) Sustainability questions; (2) Competitive response will come; (3) Investment tailwind, but plan for normalization","Random market behaviour","Declining market"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Fast-growth market analysis: (1) 12% vs 2.5% GDP = 4.8x GDP multiple; (2) Structural drivers to identify: demographics (aging population, consumer behaviour), technology (adoption, disruption), regulation (compliance, mandates), value migration (from alternatives); (3) Growth sustainability assessment: how long can growth rate continue?; (4) Competitive response: high growth attracts new entrants, capital, innovation; (5) Tailwind vs. headwind for target. For PE: (1) Faster growth supports investment thesis; (2) Multiple expansion potential if growth drives multiple premium; (3) Operational scaling critical; (4) Eventually growth normalizes (mean reversion to lower rates). Plan for multi-year investment horizon with adjustment for maturation.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD analysis reveals the target has 15% market share in a fragmented market (top 5 players at 45%). What competitive positioning does this represent?', '["Dominant position","Top-tier player in fragmented market: (1) Not dominant (45% top 5 suggests no monopoly); (2) Strong position among competitive set; (3) Consolidation opportunity exists; (4) Scale advantages developing; (5) Bolt-on potential; fragmented market supports buy-and-build strategies","Market leader","Niche player"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Market positioning analysis: (1) Target: 15% share; (2) Top 5 total: 45% share; (3) Target in top 5 but not dominant; (4) Market fragmentation: remaining 55% held by smaller players; (5) Consolidation opportunity: target could be platform for M&A roll-up. PE implications: (1) Fragmented market: supports buy-and-build strategy; (2) Smaller competitors as bolt-on targets; (3) Scale advantages build over time; (4) Customer relationships transfer; (5) Cost synergies from consolidation; (6) Market leadership becomes achievable. Strategic positioning: (1) Use target as platform; (2) Accelerate share gain through acquisitions; (3) Operational excellence as differentiator; (4) Target 25-30% share through consolidation; (5) Exit at meaningful multiple premium.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team is evaluating customer concentration. The target''s top 5 customers represent 65% of revenue. What does this reveal?', '["Healthy diversification","Significant concentration risk: (1) Customer loss could materially impact business; (2) Negotiation leverage with concentrated customers; (3) Relationship-dependence; (4) Potential for contract/pricing erosion; (5) Requires detailed analysis of each top customer''s health, contract terms, relationship strength","Low risk","Random concentration"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Customer concentration analysis: (1) Top 5 at 65% revenue: HIGH concentration; (2) Thresholds: <30% (diversified), 30-50% (moderate), >50% (high), >70% (very high); (3) Risk factors: loss of major customer, contract renegotiation, customer financial distress, relationship-dependent. Detailed analysis required: (1) Each top customer''s revenue contribution; (2) Relationship strength, switching costs; (3) Contract terms, renewal timing; (4) Customer''s financial health; (5) Strategic importance to customer; (6) Historical retention patterns. PE protective measures: (1) Structured deal: price reflects concentration risk; (2) Contracts at favourable renewal; (3) Customer lock-in through integration; (4) Diversification strategy post-acquisition; (5) Premium valuation for high-quality anchor customers.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team conducts ''voice of customer'' interviews. What is the primary value?', '["Pleasant conversation","Direct customer perspectives on: (1) Product/service quality; (2) Pricing satisfaction; (3) Switching likelihood; (4) Relationship strength; (5) Competitor comparison; (6) Future demand signals; cross-validates management''s narrative; uncovers hidden risks or opportunities","Random information","Only for marketing"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Voice-of-customer (VOC) interviews value: (1) Direct customer input: unfiltered, independent perspectives; (2) Quality assessment: real customer experience; (3) Pricing validation: sensitivity, satisfaction; (4) Switching likelihood: retention evidence; (5) Relationship depth: loyalty, length of relationship, renewal likelihood; (6) Competitor comparison: strength vs. alternatives; (7) Future demand: signals for growth/decline. Methodology: (1) 15-30 interviews per customer segment; (2) Structured questionnaire; (3) Independent interviewer (consultant); (4) Anonymity for candor; (5) Comparative scoring; (6) Triangulation with management. Critical insight sources: customer concerns not shared with management, relationship deterioration, emerging demand changes, competitor evaluation.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD analysis identifies a target''s ''competitive moat.'' What typical elements support moat assessment?', '["Random factors","Moat factors: (1) Scale advantages (cost structure); (2) Switching costs (customer lock-in); (3) Network effects (platform value); (4) Brand and intellectual property; (5) Regulatory barriers; (6) Proprietary technology; (7) Talent concentration; (8) Contract structures; strength determines competitive durability","Only price","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Competitive moat assessment: (1) Scale advantages: cost structure benefits at volume (volume discounts, overhead leverage); (2) Switching costs: customer lock-in through integration, training, transition costs; (3) Network effects: platform value grows with user/customer base; (4) Brand/IP: reputation, patents, trademarks creating barriers; (5) Regulatory barriers: licenses, certifications, compliance requirements; (6) Proprietary technology: unique capability, development expertise; (7) Talent concentration: key personnel, relationships; (8) Contract structures: long-term agreements, exclusive relationships. Assessment: (1) Multiple moats stronger than single; (2) Sustainability: will moat persist 5-10 years?; (3) Erosion risk: technology, new entrants, regulatory change; (4) Strength relative to competitors; (5) Investment required to maintain. Durable moats support premium valuations.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team analyses the target''s pricing power. The target has raised prices 3% annually for 5 years with minimal customer loss. What does this demonstrate?', '["Normal market behaviour","Strong pricing power: (1) Customers accept price increases; (2) Market position enables premium pricing; (3) Differentiated product/service; (4) Limited substitute pressure; (5) Could sustain pricing in inflation environment; fundamental quality indicator","Weak position","Customer vulnerability"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pricing power analysis: (1) Consistent 3% annual price increases; (2) Minimal customer loss (validates acceptance); (3) Indicates: strong differentiation, customer value recognition, limited substitute pressure, sticky customer relationships; (4) Testing: (a) Review customer complaints; (b) Competitor pricing trends; (c) Customer churn rates; (d) Contract structures; (e) Industry pricing dynamics. PE implications: (1) Premium valuation multiples; (2) Inflation resilience (can pass through cost increases); (3) Margin sustainability; (4) Structural competitive advantage. Comparison: weaker pricing power targets have customer losses when prices raised, price sensitivity in contracts, limited differentiation. Sustained pricing power over multiple years is strong indicator of durable competitive advantage.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies that the target''s revenue is 70% recurring (subscription/long-term contracts). How does this affect PE investment thesis?', '["No effect","Strong recurring revenue base supports: (1) Predictability of cash flows; (2) Higher valuation multiples (typically 1-3x premium); (3) Better leverage capacity; (4) More stable business through cycles; (5) Reduced risk of sudden revenue loss; fundamental quality indicator supporting LBO suitability","Reduces attractiveness","Random impact"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Recurring revenue analysis: (1) 70% recurring base: strong foundation; (2) Benefits: predictable cash flows (visibility), higher valuations (1-3x multiple premium), stability through cycles, greater leverage capacity; (3) Renewal rates: critical to validate recurring base; (4) Customer concentration within recurring base; (5) Contract terms and durations. Typical patterns: (1) SaaS: 90%+ recurring; (2) Services: 50-80% recurring; (3) Distribution: variable but often 60-80% recurring customer relationships; (4) Manufacturing: 30-60% recurring. For PE analysis: (1) Higher recurring = premium valuation; (2) Supports more leverage; (3) Smoother cash flow profile; (4) Lower operational risk; (5) Attractive exit profile. Validation: historical retention, contract terms, customer satisfaction.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team evaluates the target''s distribution/channel model. The target sells 60% direct-to-customer and 40% through distributors. What analysis is appropriate?', '["Ignore channel","Channel analysis: (1) Channel profitability comparison; (2) Distributor relationships strength; (3) Channel conflict (direct vs. distributor); (4) Channel evolution trends; (5) Customer preference; (6) Distribution economics (gross to net); fundamental to understanding business model","Only direct","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Channel model analysis: (1) Profitability by channel: direct typically higher margin (keep distributor margin), but distributor provides scale; (2) Relationship assessment: long-standing distributors with exclusivity valuable; (3) Channel conflict: direct competing with distributors creates tensions; (4) Channel evolution: digital direct-to-consumer transition; (5) Customer preference: digital natives prefer direct; (6) Economics: distributor margins (typically 10-25% of revenue), incentives, inventory. Strategic questions: (1) Is mix optimal? (2) Is channel evolving in target''s favour?; (3) Are distributor relationships durable?; (4) Opportunity to shift mix post-acquisition?; (5) Digital transformation implications. Sophisticated CDD includes channel economics, competitive positioning, and evolution trends.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team analyses the target''s geographic footprint. 80% of revenue is domestic; target has modest international presence. What does this reveal?', '["Diversified","Concentrated geographic risk: (1) Dependence on single economy; (2) Currency risk limited but economic cycle exposure high; (3) Growth potential: international expansion opportunity; (4) Market maturity: domestic often mature; (5) Operational simplicity but growth ceiling; analysis includes expansion potential and international strategy","Perfect balance","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Geographic analysis: (1) 80% domestic concentration: exposure to single economy; (2) Economic cycle risk: downturn in primary market impacts 80% of revenue; (3) Growth constraint: mature domestic markets grow slowly; (4) Currency risk: limited (single currency exposure); (5) International potential: 20% international shows feasibility; expansion opportunity. Expansion analysis: (1) Target markets for growth; (2) Competitive landscape internationally; (3) Regulatory differences; (4) Infrastructure requirements; (5) Investment needed; (6) Management capability; (7) Strategic fit. PE thesis: (1) Use platform status to expand internationally; (2) Capital deployment for expansion; (3) Margin pressure initially but scale benefits long-term; (4) Exit with international presence at premium valuation; (5) Multiple arbitrage on internationalized business.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies emerging technology disruption in the target''s industry. How does this affect the analysis?', '["Ignore technology trends","Scenario analysis: (1) Disruption timeline (when becomes material); (2) Impact assessment (who wins/loses); (3) Target''s response capability; (4) Investment required to adapt; (5) Alternative scenarios including exit timing; (6) Mitigation or positioning strategy","Always avoid","Random response"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Technology disruption analysis: (1) Timeline: when does disruption become material? 5-10 years typical; (2) Impact assessment: (a) Who benefits? (b) Who loses?; (3) Target''s capability: (a) Current technology adoption; (b) R&D resources; (c) Management awareness and response; (4) Investment required: capex, technology licensing, acquisitions; (5) Scenarios: (a) Successful adaptation; (b) Gradual decline; (c) Disruption capture; (d) Failed adaptation; (6) Mitigation: (a) Acquire emerging competitors; (b) Develop capabilities; (c) Exit before decline. Strategic response: (1) Proactive adaptation; (2) Operational transformation; (3) M&A for capability; (4) Potential exit timing before disruption; (5) Risk adjustment in valuation. Disruption shouldn''t always prevent investment but requires clear response.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team examines the target''s ''new customer acquisition'' economics. What''s typically measured?', '["Random metrics","Customer acquisition cost (CAC): total sales and marketing spend / new customers acquired. Indicators: CAC trend, sales efficiency (Magic Number), customer lifetime value vs CAC, payback period; reveals business''s ability to grow profitably","Only headcount","Only revenue"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Customer acquisition economics: (1) Customer Acquisition Cost (CAC): total S&M spend / new customers; (2) CAC trend: rising (bad) or stable/declining (good); (3) Sales efficiency (Magic Number): ARR gained / S&M spend; >1 is efficient; (4) Customer Lifetime Value (LTV): revenue per customer × retention period / discount rate; (5) LTV:CAC ratio: 3x+ is healthy; (6) Payback period: months to recoup CAC. Red flags: (1) Rising CAC over time; (2) LTV:CAC below 3x; (3) Payback period >2-3 years; (4) Sales efficiency <0.7. Green flags: (1) Declining CAC through scale; (2) LTV:CAC >5x; (3) Payback <18 months; (4) Efficient sales model (digital, direct). These metrics reveal whether growth is profitable and sustainable.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team analyses customer retention patterns. Annual retention is 85%, while best-in-class peers achieve 95%. What does this gap suggest?', '["No difference","Meaningful gap: (1) 10 percentage point difference is material; (2) Suggests weaker customer satisfaction, product differentiation, or service quality; (3) Opportunity: improvement to peer levels adds value; (4) Risk: continued attrition depresses performance; (5) Value creation lever for PE: retention improvement initiatives","Excellent performance","Random variation"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Retention gap analysis: (1) Target: 85% retention; (2) Best-in-class: 95%; (3) Gap: 10 percentage points; (4) Impact: target loses 15% annually vs. 5%; over 5 years: (a) 95% retention: compounds to ~78%; (b) 85% retention: compounds to ~44%. Significant long-term impact. Analysis: (1) Root causes — product, service, pricing, support?; (2) Customer segment patterns — which lose retention?; (3) Churn drivers — competitive, satisfaction, changing needs?; (4) Customer lifetime value implications. PE opportunity: (1) Value creation: improve retention from 85% to 90-92%; (2) Revenue impact: meaningful incremental; (3) Margin benefit: lower customer acquisition required; (4) Higher valuation at exit; (5) Operational initiatives: customer success programs, service improvements, product enhancements.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team evaluates the target''s sales team effectiveness. Quota attainment is 60%, compared to 75% best-in-class. What does this suggest?', '["Excellent performance","Sales effectiveness issue: (1) Below best-in-class by meaningful margin; (2) Possible causes: poor sales enablement, quota setting issues, product-market fit problems, compensation structure, talent gaps; (3) Opportunity: sales optimisation adds meaningful revenue; (4) Critical PE value creation lever","Normal variation","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sales effectiveness gap analysis: (1) 60% quota attainment vs 75% best-in-class; (2) Impact: if quota represents targeted revenue, 15pp gap is meaningful; (3) Root causes to investigate: (a) Quota setting — unrealistic targets?; (b) Sales enablement — training, tools, collateral?; (c) Product-market fit — right product for market?; (d) Compensation structure — aligned with goals?; (e) Talent gaps — recruiting and retention?; (f) Sales management — leadership, processes?. PE improvement opportunities: (1) Better sales training and enablement; (2) Improved CRM and sales tools; (3) Talent upgrade where needed; (4) Compensation restructuring; (5) Process improvements; (6) Performance management discipline. Quick wins possible in 6-12 months with focused investment and attention.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies 3 main competitors with similar offerings. What''s the key analysis?', '["Only price comparison","Comprehensive competitive analysis: (1) Market share trends over time; (2) Capability comparison (product, service, operational); (3) Customer base differences; (4) Financial performance comparison; (5) Strategic direction; (6) Recent actions (acquisitions, products); (7) Relative strengths and weaknesses","Random analysis","Only competitor names"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Competitive analysis framework: (1) Market share trends: stable, gaining, or losing; (2) Financial comparison: revenue, margins, growth rates, returns; (3) Capability comparison: product depth, service quality, technology, scale; (4) Customer base: similarities and differences; (5) Strategic direction: where are competitors heading?; (6) Recent actions: acquisitions, new products, market entries; (7) Pricing positioning: premium, mid-market, value; (8) Strengths and weaknesses assessment. Key insights: (1) Is target gaining or losing share? (direction matters); (2) What are target''s relative advantages?; (3) What are main threats?; (4) Strategic positioning vs. competitors. Sophisticated CDD goes beyond simple peer benchmarking to understand dynamic competitive positioning and trajectory.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team analyses the target''s product/service portfolio. Portfolio has 3 core products plus 2 non-core legacy products. What does this reveal?', '["No significance","Portfolio complexity indicates: (1) Resource dilution (managing non-core drains attention); (2) Legacy products may distract from growth; (3) Rationalisation opportunity (divest non-core); (4) Simplification benefit (focus); (5) Operational efficiency gains post-rationalisation; classic PE value creation lever","Always diversify","Random composition"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Portfolio rationalisation analysis: (1) 3 core + 2 non-core = 40% of products non-strategic; (2) Resource dilution: R&D, sales, operations resources spread thin; (3) Management attention: non-core distracts from growth opportunities; (4) Margin impact: often non-core lower margin; (5) Competitive focus: core products need full attention to compete. PE rationalisation actions: (1) Divest non-core to strategic buyer; (2) End-of-life legacy products gradually; (3) Reallocate resources to core; (4) Simplify organisation; (5) Improve operational efficiency. Benefits: (1) Revenue reallocation to higher-margin core; (2) Cost reduction from simplification; (3) Faster decision-making; (4) Cleaner valuation at exit; (5) Multiple expansion from focus. Classic early 100-day initiative for PE.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team is evaluating market cyclicality. The target''s sector showed 20% revenue decline in 2008, 15% decline in 2020. What does this imply?', '["Recession-proof","High cyclicality: 15-20% declines in downturns significant: (1) EBITDA volatility high; (2) Leverage needs to be conservative; (3) Downside scenarios need modelling; (4) Covenant risk in downturns; (5) Valuation discount for cyclicality; structural consideration for LBO suitability","Random performance","Neutral impact"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Cyclicality analysis: (1) 2008: 20% decline (Great Recession); (2) 2020: 15% decline (COVID); (3) High cyclicality pattern; (4) EBITDA volatility proportional — margins typically squeeze in downturn, amplifying EBITDA volatility. LBO implications: (1) Conservative leverage: 3-4x EBITDA (vs 5-6x for stable); (2) Covenant cushion: need significant headroom; (3) Interest coverage: must survive downturn EBITDA; (4) Downside scenarios: -25% EBITDA stress test; (5) Multiple compression likely in downturns. Valuation impact: (1) Lower multiples than stable peers; (2) Discount for cyclical exposure; (3) Exit multiple timing critical (avoid peak). Strategic adjustments: (1) Revenue diversification; (2) Cost flexibility; (3) Fixed cost reduction; (4) Contract structuring; (5) International expansion for counter-cyclical exposure.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies ''regulatory risk'' as a concern. How is this assessed?', '["Ignore regulation","Regulatory assessment: (1) Current regulatory framework; (2) Upcoming changes (anticipated legislation); (3) Political climate; (4) Industry lobbying effectiveness; (5) Compliance investments required; (6) Potential impact on business model; (7) Sector precedents; (8) Mitigation strategies","Only current rules","Random assessment"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Regulatory risk assessment: (1) Current framework: what rules apply, compliance costs?; (2) Upcoming changes: identified proposals, likelihood of passage, timing; (3) Political climate: direction of policy (tightening, loosening); (4) Industry influence: lobbying effectiveness, political positioning; (5) Compliance investments: capex, IT, personnel for changes; (6) Business model impact: pricing power, customer behaviour, competitive position; (7) Sector precedents: how similar industries responded; (8) Mitigation: geographical shifts, product modifications, strategic moves. For PE analysis: (1) Regulatory risk affects long-term value; (2) Timing of regulation vs. hold period; (3) Compliance costs in modeling; (4) Pricing pass-through capability; (5) Exit buyer willingness. Heavy regulation often creates moats but also requires investment and vigilance.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team examines customer satisfaction scores. Net Promoter Score (NPS) is 35, compared to industry benchmark of 50. What does this suggest?', '["Excellent performance","Below-average satisfaction: (1) 35 vs. 50 benchmark is meaningful gap; (2) Customer dissatisfaction affects retention, referrals, pricing power; (3) Drivers to investigate: product, service, pricing, support; (4) Improvement opportunity: move to 50+; (5) Value creation lever: service/product improvements","Best-in-class","Random measure"]'::jsonb, 1, 'NPS interpretation: (1) NPS range: -100 (all detractors) to +100 (all promoters); (2) Target: 35 (positive but below benchmark); (3) Industry benchmark: 50 (strong); (4) Gap: 15 points is meaningful; (5) Category: ''average'' performance vs ''good/excellent'' for benchmark. Business impact: (1) Retention: lower NPS correlates with lower retention; (2) Referrals: fewer customer-to-customer endorsements; (3) Pricing power: satisfied customers accept price increases; (4) Growth: lower organic growth from customer base; (5) Revenue expansion: lower upsell rates. Value creation opportunities: (1) Service improvements; (2) Product enhancements; (3) Customer success programs; (4) Faster issue resolution; (5) Proactive communication. Moving NPS from 35 to 50 typically takes 12-24 months with focused initiatives.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies the target has 5-year contracts with 70% of top customers. What does this reveal?', '["Random pattern","Strong customer lock-in: (1) Revenue visibility for 5-year period; (2) Retention likely for contract duration; (3) Supports LBO thesis (predictable cash flow); (4) Higher valuation multiples; (5) Switching costs embedded; (6) Contract terms critical (renewal, pricing mechanisms)","Weak position","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Long-term contract analysis: (1) 5-year contracts with 70% of top customers: strong lock-in; (2) Revenue visibility: predictable for contract duration; (3) Retention: implicit commitment; (4) Switching costs: contractual obligations create inertia; (5) Supports LBO thesis: predictable cash flows for debt service. Contract terms matter: (1) Pricing mechanisms (fixed, escalation, indexed); (2) Renewal terms (automatic, negotiated); (3) Performance metrics; (4) Termination provisions; (5) Exclusivity. For PE analysis: (1) Contract roll-off timing during hold period; (2) Renewal success rates historically; (3) Pricing escalation clauses; (4) Strategic customer relationship strength beyond contract; (5) Value at stake in renewals. Premium for long-term contracts but investigate: are they profitable? Locked in at outdated pricing? Renewal risk?'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team examines the target''s digital transformation progress. Assessment shows moderate digital maturity vs. best-in-class. What''s the interpretation?', '["No action needed","Moderate gap represents: (1) Investment opportunity in digital capabilities; (2) Competitive risk from digital natives; (3) Operational efficiency opportunity; (4) Customer experience improvement; (5) Potential value creation lever; (6) Execution risk if transformation not managed","Perfect position","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Digital maturity analysis: (1) Moderate vs. best-in-class: meaningful gap; (2) Risk dimensions: (a) Competitive vulnerability to digital natives; (b) Customer expectations rising; (c) Operational efficiency gaps; (d) Employee experience concerns; (3) Opportunity dimensions: (a) Digital transformation investment; (b) Customer experience improvement; (c) Operational automation; (d) Data analytics capabilities. PE value creation: (1) Digital investment as value creation lever; (2) Typically €10-30M capex over 2-3 years; (3) Benefits: efficiency gains, customer experience, data insights; (4) Risks: execution complexity, cultural resistance, technology choices. Framework: (1) Current digital maturity audit; (2) Gap identification; (3) Investment roadmap; (4) Priority sequence; (5) Capability development plan; (6) Success metrics. Digital transformation is increasingly critical to value creation.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team evaluates the target''s pricing strategy. The target uses cost-plus pricing with 25% margin standardised across products. What does this reveal?', '["Optimal strategy","Suboptimal pricing: (1) Cost-plus ignores customer value perception; (2) Missing opportunities for premium pricing on differentiated products; (3) Value-based pricing could increase margins; (4) Market research reveals willingness-to-pay; (5) Significant value creation opportunity through pricing optimisation","Random pricing","Perfect approach"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pricing strategy analysis: (1) Cost-plus pricing: simple but suboptimal; (2) 25% margin standardised: missing product-specific value; (3) Inefficiencies: (a) Premium products underpriced; (b) Commodity products possibly overpriced; (c) Customer value unexplored. Value-based pricing opportunity: (1) Research customer willingness-to-pay; (2) Segment customers by value; (3) Price differentiation by product tier; (4) Premium products at premium prices; (5) Value products competitively priced. Impact: (1) Gross margin improvement: 3-5% typical; (2) Revenue growth from premium positioning; (3) Profit expansion through segmentation; (4) Customer alignment (pay for what they value). PE value creation lever: pricing optimisation is often among highest ROI initiatives. Requires: customer research, pricing analytics, sales training, implementation discipline.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies the target''s growth has slowed from 12% to 6% over 3 years. What analysis is warranted?', '["Ignore the trend","Root cause analysis: (1) Market growth deceleration?; (2) Competitive pressure?; (3) Customer saturation?; (4) Product maturity?; (5) Management challenges?; (6) Execution issues?; (7) Pricing limits?; understanding cause determines whether deceleration is temporary or structural","Always decline","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Growth deceleration analysis: (1) 12% to 6% is material slowdown; (2) Multiple potential causes require investigation: (a) Market: is overall market slowing?; (b) Competitive: market share losses to competitors?; (c) Saturation: core customer base maturing?; (d) Product: core offerings reaching end-of-life?; (e) Management: leadership issues or strategic errors?; (f) Execution: operational challenges?; (g) Pricing: pushing against customer tolerance?. Analysis process: (1) Decompose growth by segment, customer, product; (2) Interview management on their view; (3) Customer research (VOC); (4) Competitive landscape analysis; (5) Market trend research. PE implications: (1) If temporary, opportunity to accelerate; (2) If structural, requires transformation thesis; (3) Pricing reflects growth reality; (4) Exit multiple considerations.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team analyses the target''s ''market position'' relative to competitors. What dimensions are typically assessed?', '["Random dimensions","Multiple dimensions: (1) Market share and trend; (2) Revenue growth vs. peers; (3) Margin performance vs. peers; (4) Customer base (quality, concentration); (5) Product portfolio depth; (6) Brand and reputation; (7) Operational capabilities; (8) Management team; (9) Financial strength; (10) Strategic flexibility","Only revenue","Only market share"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Market position assessment dimensions: (1) Market share: scale advantages, customer recognition; (2) Revenue growth: momentum vs. competition; (3) Margins: operational effectiveness, pricing power; (4) Customer base: quality (enterprise vs SMB), concentration, retention; (5) Product portfolio: depth and breadth; (6) Brand/reputation: awareness, preference; (7) Operational capabilities: technology, scale, efficiency; (8) Management team: talent, experience, capability; (9) Financial strength: balance sheet, access to capital; (10) Strategic flexibility: adaptation capability. Analysis framework: (1) Relative ranking on each dimension; (2) Weighted by importance; (3) Trend analysis (gaining, stable, declining); (4) Competitive response capability. Strong positioning across multiple dimensions supports premium valuation; weak position or declining trend raises concerns.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team evaluates the target''s ''customer lifetime value'' (LTV). LTV is €250K, CAC is €85K. What does this suggest?', '["Unhealthy economics","Healthy economics: (1) LTV:CAC ratio = 2.94x (approaching healthy 3x threshold); (2) Customer acquisition profitable; (3) Revenue per customer sustainable; (4) Payback achievable; (5) Room for improvement — best-in-class LTV:CAC >5x","Random values","Perfect metrics"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LTV:CAC analysis: (1) Ratio = €250K / €85K = 2.94x; (2) Threshold: 3x considered healthy; 5x+ is strong; <2x indicates unprofitable growth; (3) Interpretation: (a) Business generates €2.94 in value for every €1 invested in acquisition; (b) Payback period achievable; (c) Growth is profitable; (4) Improvement opportunities: (a) Increase LTV (retention, upsell, pricing); (b) Reduce CAC (efficiency, organic growth, referrals); (c) Move toward 5x ratio. PE analysis: (1) Current ratio supports investment thesis; (2) Improvement to 4-5x creates meaningful value; (3) Operational initiatives: customer success, product enhancements, sales efficiency; (4) Growth investment justified; (5) Competitive position sustainable. Metric triangulates with retention, pricing, sales effectiveness for comprehensive picture.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies that the target has limited growth investment (R&D at 1% of revenue vs. industry 3-5%). What does this suggest?', '["Efficient business","Underinvestment concern: (1) Industry invests 3-5% in R&D; (2) Target at 1% is meaningful underinvestment; (3) Risks: product obsolescence, competitive vulnerability, growth deceleration; (4) PE opportunity: increase investment, faster innovation; (5) Trade-off: short-term margin vs. long-term growth","Perfect efficiency","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'R&D underinvestment analysis: (1) Target 1% vs industry 3-5%; (2) Significant underinvestment; (3) Potential implications: (a) Aging product portfolio; (b) Competitive vulnerability to innovators; (c) Gradual market share erosion; (d) Declining growth rate trajectory; (e) Dependence on legacy products. PE response framework: (1) Invest in catch-up R&D; typically 2-3% increase; (2) Focus on impactful products; (3) M&A for capability acquisition; (4) Partnerships for technology access; (5) Management investment. Timeline: (1) Increased R&D: immediate margin impact; (2) Innovation results: 2-3 year timeline; (3) Revenue impact: lagged by additional 1-2 years; (4) Value creation over hold period. Balance: short-term margin vs. long-term sustainability. Sometimes undervaluation opportunity if turnaround thesis validated.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team is examining ''substitute threat'' in the target''s market. What analysis is performed?', '["Only direct competitors","Comprehensive substitute analysis: (1) Direct substitutes (same function, different form); (2) Indirect substitutes (different approach to same need); (3) Customer alternatives (DIY, internal development, no-purchase); (4) Emerging technologies; (5) Market forces driving substitution; (6) Mitigation strategies","Random threats","No threats"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Substitute threat analysis: (1) Direct substitutes: different products/services serving same customer need; (2) Indirect substitutes: different approaches to same problem; (3) Customer alternatives: Do-it-yourself (reduce demand), internal development (enterprise customers), no-purchase (delay or forgo); (4) Emerging technologies: disruptive capabilities; (5) Market dynamics: economic, demographic, social drivers of substitution; (6) Mitigation: product improvement, customer lock-in, value pricing. Example: traditional software vs. SaaS: (1) Customer wants software solution; (2) Direct substitute: competing traditional software; (3) Indirect substitute: open source tools; (4) Alternative: manual processes, outsourcing. Analysis reveals: (1) Near-term threats; (2) Long-term positioning risks; (3) Required strategic adaptation; (4) Investment priorities; (5) Business model evolution needs.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team evaluates the target''s ''growth trajectory.'' Historical revenue shows +8%, +6%, +4%, +2% over 4 years. What pattern is this?', '["Steady growth","Decelerating growth pattern: consistent year-over-year decline in growth rate; signals: market saturation, competitive pressure, product maturity; future growth may approach zero or negative; concerning for PE investment thesis","Accelerating growth","Random pattern"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Growth deceleration pattern analysis: (1) Declining growth rates: 8% → 6% → 4% → 2%; (2) Consistent deceleration suggests structural pattern; (3) Projection: likely continues toward 0%; (4) Causes to identify: (a) Market saturation; (b) Competitive intensification; (c) Product maturity/decline; (d) Pricing constraints; (e) Cyclical decline. Significance: (1) Declining growth reduces valuation multiples; (2) Exit multiple likely lower; (3) Return generation harder; (4) Value creation thesis must address growth. PE options: (1) Accelerate growth through investment (new products, markets, channels); (2) M&A for growth; (3) Cost programs to maintain margins despite slower growth; (4) Pricing optimisation; (5) International expansion. Reality check: (1) Many ''growth'' businesses are actually decelerating; (2) Careful growth analysis essential; (3) Decline before value creation plan.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team analyses the target''s revenue mix. 40% subscription-recurring, 30% project-based, 20% professional services, 10% one-time. What does this mix reveal?', '["Perfect diversification","Mix reveals: (1) Moderate recurring base (40% subscription); (2) Significant variable business (50% project/professional); (3) Mixed business model; (4) Recurring could be strengthened; (5) Project business has volatility; (6) Valuation mix (multiples differ by revenue type)","Only recurring","All one-time"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Revenue mix analysis: (1) Subscription (40%): recurring, predictable, high multiples; (2) Project-based (30%): variable, lower margins, moderate multiples; (3) Professional services (20%): typically project-linked, consistent with implementation; (4) One-time (10%): unpredictable, lowest multiples. Overall interpretation: (1) Only 40% purely recurring: moderate LBO candidate quality; (2) 50% variable business creates volatility; (3) Mixed valuation: composite of different multiples; (4) PE improvement: shift mix toward recurring. Strategic levers: (1) Convert project to subscription model; (2) Expand subscription products; (3) Customer contract restructuring; (4) Pricing model changes; (5) Recurring revenue from installed base. Impact: (1) Higher blended multiples; (2) Stronger leverage capacity; (3) Better cash flow predictability; (4) Premium exit valuation. Shifting mix over 5-year hold can significantly enhance value.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies the target has a ''strategic advantage'' in customer relationship. How is relationship strength assessed?', '["Random assessment","Multi-dimensional assessment: (1) Length of relationships (years); (2) Contract structures; (3) Customer engagement frequency; (4) Expansion history (same customers buying more); (5) Referral patterns; (6) Customer participation in R&D; (7) Integration depth (technology, processes)","Only length","Only revenue"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Customer relationship strength assessment: (1) Duration: long relationships (5+ years) indicate quality; (2) Contract structures: long-term, exclusive, multi-year; (3) Engagement: frequency, executive relationships; (4) Expansion: existing customers growing spend; (5) Referrals: willingness to refer; (6) Collaboration: participating in R&D, feedback; (7) Integration: technical/process integration creating switching costs. Example deep relationships: (1) 10+ year relationships; (2) Multi-year contracts; (3) Integrated technology platforms; (4) Joint product development; (5) Strong executive relationships at multiple levels; (6) Customer as reference for new prospects. Metrics: customer retention, NPS, expansion rates, contract renewal rates, customer lifetime value. Deep relationships are: (1) Significant competitive moat; (2) Difficult to replicate; (3) Revenue predictability; (4) Pricing power; (5) Strategic value. Well-documented strong relationships justify premium valuation.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team evaluates a target where management projects 20% revenue growth next year. How is this validated?', '["Accept at face value","Rigorous validation: (1) Historical growth pattern; (2) Market growth rate; (3) Sales pipeline analysis; (4) Customer commitments; (5) Competitive dynamics; (6) Operational capacity; (7) Management track record; (8) Sector benchmarking; validated projection influences pricing and returns","Always reject","Random approach"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Projection validation framework: (1) Historical growth pattern — consistent with projection?; (2) Market growth — target growing faster than market is realistic?; (3) Sales pipeline — quantity and quality of opportunities; (4) Customer commitments — signed contracts, letter of intent; (5) Competitive dynamics — is competitor losing share?; (6) Operational capacity — can the business scale?; (7) Management track record — have they delivered past projections?; (8) Sector benchmarking — is growth plausible for peers?; (9) Cyclical factors — is growth tailwind or headwind?. Assessment outcomes: (1) Validated: build into base case; (2) Partially validated: adjust to more realistic rate; (3) Not validated: conservative growth assumption. For LBO model: (1) Use conservative validated rate, not management''s aspirational; (2) Upside case can include management number; (3) Returns based on realistic projections; (4) Margin of safety built in.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies the target''s ''growth drivers'' include new product launches planned. What analysis is performed?', '["Accept projections","Product launch analysis: (1) Product development stage; (2) Target market size; (3) Competitive positioning; (4) Differentiation; (5) Distribution readiness; (6) Pricing strategy; (7) Customer feedback/testing; (8) Launch timeline; (9) Revenue ramp assumptions; (10) Success probability","Random assessment","Only revenue"]'::jsonb, 1, 'New product launch analysis: (1) Development stage: concept, prototype, alpha, beta, production; (2) Target market: size, growth, customer readiness; (3) Competitive positioning: differentiated, parity, follower; (4) Differentiation: why customers will buy; (5) Distribution: channels ready, salesforce trained; (6) Pricing strategy: premium, competitive, value; (7) Customer feedback: beta testing, pre-orders, pilot programs; (8) Launch timeline: realistic, dependency mapping; (9) Revenue ramp: first year, year 2-3 projections; (10) Success probability: based on development stage, market acceptance. Typical success rates: (1) Early stage: 20-40% commercial success; (2) Late stage/beta: 60-80%; (3) Pre-launch: 50-70%; (4) Launched with traction: 80-95%. CDD should: (1) Discount management projections; (2) Apply success probability; (3) Consider market reaction; (4) Include launch costs and risks; (5) Model realistic ramp.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team analyses ''market consolidation'' trend. Top 10 players grew from 45% to 60% market share over 5 years. What does this indicate?', '["Random variation","Meaningful consolidation: (1) Market shifting from fragmented to consolidated; (2) Scale advantages increasing; (3) Strategic buyers paying premiums for position; (4) M&A activity accelerated; (5) Platform opportunity for PE; (6) Consolidation wave likely to continue; (7) Valuation multiples may rise with consolidation","Always bad","Randomness"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Consolidation trend analysis: (1) 45% → 60% = 15 percentage point shift toward concentration; (2) Suggests: strategic consolidators active, scale benefits apparent, market maturing; (3) Remaining 40% still fragmented: opportunity for further consolidation; (4) Valuation implications: premium multiples for consolidators. PE platform strategy: (1) Select target with consolidation position; (2) Buy-and-build through bolt-ons; (3) Capture scale benefits; (4) Multiple arbitrage: bolt-ons at 6-8x, exit at 10-12x platform; (5) Strategic exit at premium valuation. Risks to monitor: (1) Regulatory pushback (antitrust); (2) Execution (integration challenges); (3) Price increases from consolidation; (4) Customer resistance; (5) Technology disruption during consolidation. Sophisticated PE firms build platforms in consolidating markets: significant value creation but execution intensive.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies that a key competitor is ''strategically pivoting'' away from the target''s segment. How does this affect analysis?', '["Ignore","Favorable development: (1) Reduced competitive intensity; (2) Market share opportunity; (3) Customer migration potential; (4) Pricing power improvement; (5) Strategic positioning strengthens; but: (1) Understand why competitor pivoting; (2) Timing of their exit; (3) Market reaction","Neutral","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Competitor pivot analysis: (1) Direct benefit: reduced competition in target''s segment; (2) Market share opportunity: capture customers previously served by departing competitor; (3) Pricing improvement: fewer competitors supports premium pricing; (4) Strategic positioning: gap in market created. Caveats: (1) Why is competitor leaving? (Might indicate sector issues); (2) Timing of their exit (how long until market impact); (3) What takes their place? (New entrants, substitutes?); (4) Customer loyalty (do customers follow departing competitor?). For PE investment: (1) If validated market dynamic, favorable; (2) Valuation should reflect improved position; (3) Strategic opportunity to gain share; (4) Pricing power enhancement; (5) Potential customer acquisition. Combined with other factors: competitor pivots can reinforce positive investment thesis. Track execution of competitor''s pivot and market reaction to validate thesis.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team''s analysis culminates in an ''investment thesis'' document. What does this typically include?', '["Random observations","Comprehensive thesis: (1) Market opportunity; (2) Target''s competitive advantages; (3) Customer relationships and retention; (4) Growth drivers; (5) Value creation plan; (6) Key risks and mitigants; (7) Financial projections; (8) Exit thesis; (9) Supporting evidence; (10) Confidence factors","Only projections","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Investment thesis document structure: (1) Executive summary: key insights; (2) Market opportunity: size, growth, dynamics; (3) Target''s competitive advantages: moats, market position; (4) Customer relationships: quality, retention, satisfaction; (5) Growth drivers: specific levers, validation; (6) Value creation plan: specific initiatives, timeline; (7) Key risks: identified with mitigants; (8) Financial projections: based on validated assumptions; (9) Exit thesis: likely buyers, timing, multiples; (10) Confidence factors: why we believe this investment works; (11) Conditions: what must be true for success; (12) Walk-away factors: red flags that would change decision. Purpose: (1) IC decision-making; (2) LP communication; (3) Team alignment; (4) Monitoring framework; (5) Post-close guide. Sophisticated firms produce rigorous thesis documents. Weak thesis: investment often struggles; strong thesis: higher success rate.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team presents findings to the IC. What format is appropriate?', '["Only verbal","Formal presentation: (1) Executive summary; (2) Market analysis; (3) Competitive positioning; (4) Customer insights; (5) Growth drivers; (6) Risk analysis; (7) Investment thesis; (8) Supporting data; (9) Q&A preparation; provides comprehensive foundation for IC decision","Random","Only charts"]'::jsonb, 1, 'CDD IC presentation structure: (1) Executive summary (1-2 slides): recommendation, key findings, thesis; (2) Market analysis: size, growth, dynamics, structure; (3) Competitive positioning: strengths, weaknesses, relative position; (4) Customer insights: voice-of-customer, retention, quality; (5) Growth drivers: specific levers, validation, projections; (6) Risk analysis: identified risks, severity, mitigants; (7) Investment thesis: why this deal, why now; (8) Supporting data: detailed analyses, comparisons, evidence; (9) Financial implications: valuation, projections, returns; (10) Q&A preparation: anticipate tough questions. Format: (1) Clear, data-driven; (2) Focuses on decision-relevant insights; (3) Balances findings (positive and negative); (4) Allows IC to challenge and explore; (5) 30-60 minute typical. Strong CDD presentation builds IC confidence; weak presentation raises doubts. Quality of analysis and presentation both matter.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team identifies the target''s customer ''churn rate'' at 12% annually. How does this affect valuation?', '["No effect","Material impact: (1) 12% churn = 88% retention; (2) Below typical PE target of 90%+; (3) Implications: revenue visibility, customer acquisition cost, growth efficiency; (4) Valuation multiple discount; (5) Value creation opportunity through retention improvement; (6) Focus area post-acquisition","Random","Unrelated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Churn rate analysis: (1) 12% annual churn = 88% retention; (2) Benchmarks: SaaS 95-99% gross retention; Services 85-95%; Industrial 90-95%; (3) 12% is at lower end of acceptable range; (4) Impact: (a) Revenue visibility reduced; (b) Customer acquisition cost (CAC) higher (constantly replacing lost customers); (c) Growth efficiency lower (net new growth = gross new - churn). Valuation implications: (1) Revenue multiple discount for higher churn; (2) EBITDA multiple discount reflecting cash flow volatility; (3) Value creation opportunity: reduce churn from 12% to 6-8%. PE improvement program: (1) Customer success investment; (2) Product enhancements; (3) Service quality improvements; (4) Customer segmentation; (5) Proactive retention; (6) Pricing flexibility. 5% reduction (12% to 7%) on €100M revenue: €5M annually in retained revenue; at 10x multiple = €50M enterprise value gain.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team evaluates the target''s ''expansion revenue'' from existing customers. Current expansion: 8% of existing customer base annually. What''s the interpretation?', '["Random","Meaningful expansion: (1) Customers spending more over time is healthy; (2) 8% growth shows upsell/cross-sell success; (3) Contributes to net revenue retention (expansion - churn); (4) Valuation support; (5) Operational lever: can be accelerated through account management, product expansion","Poor performance","Unhealthy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Expansion revenue analysis: (1) 8% annual expansion from existing base: meaningful; (2) Components: upsell (higher tiers), cross-sell (new products), volume growth (more of same); (3) Net Revenue Retention (NRR) = 100% + Expansion - Churn; 12% churn + 8% expansion = 96% NRR; (4) Benchmarks: best SaaS >130% NRR; average 100-110%; (5) Value creation potential: (a) Accelerate expansion through better account management; (b) New product launches; (c) Pricing optimization; (d) Customer success programs. PE value creation: (1) Current 96% NRR; (2) Target improvement to 110-120% NRR; (3) Revenue impact meaningful over 5-year hold; (4) Multiple expansion on improved metrics. Sophisticated analysis links: (1) NRR to valuation multiples; (2) Operational initiatives to financial impact; (3) Customer segment analysis; (4) Long-term customer economics.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-commercial', 'A CDD team reviews competitor win/loss data. Target wins 55% of head-to-head deals. What does this represent?', '["Weak position","Win rate above 50% indicates: (1) Strong competitive position; (2) Value proposition advantage; (3) Winning in competitive situations; (4) Opportunity for further improvement (65-70% typical for leaders); (5) Positive indicator for PE investment","Random variation","Always weak"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Win rate analysis: (1) 55% win rate in head-to-head: above 50% threshold; (2) Interpretation: value proposition works against competitors; (3) Benchmarks: (a) Market leaders: 65-75%; (b) Strong competitors: 55-65%; (c) Competitive parity: 45-55%; (d) Weaker position: <45%. Analysis depth: (1) Win rate by competitor (identify weaker vs. stronger rivals); (2) Win rate by deal size (small vs large); (3) Win rate by segment (customer types); (4) Win/loss themes (features, pricing, service, relationships); (5) Trend over time (improving or declining). PE insights: (1) Current 55% is respectable; (2) Opportunity to push to 65%+; (3) Improvement areas: product, sales effectiveness, pricing; (4) Value creation initiatives: strengthening value proposition, sales training. Higher win rates: stronger market position, premium valuation, easier growth. Win/loss analysis essential for understanding competitive reality.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm commissions Financial Due Diligence (FDD) on a target. What is the primary objective of FDD distinct from the annual audit?', '["To verify the audit opinion","To validate the sustainable earnings, assess quality of adjustments, normalise working capital, and identify accounting matters that affect the transaction — all specific to the M&A context, not the audit opinion","To replace the audit","To evaluate management"]'::jsonb, 1, 'FDD purpose vs. audit: (1) FDD: transaction-specific analysis for PE decision-making; assesses sustainable earnings, quality of adjustments, normalised working capital, debt-like items; informs pricing, structuring, post-close actions. (2) Annual audit: financial statement accuracy and GAAP/IFRS compliance; broader but less deal-specific. Scope differences: (1) FDD focuses on EBITDA quality, adjustments, WC normalisation; (2) Audit focuses on financial statement compliance; (3) FDD deeper in specific areas (EBITDA, WC, debt-like items); (4) Audit broader in scope (all financial statements). Deliverables: (1) FDD report: QofE, WC analysis, debt-like items, financial projections review; (2) Audit: financial statement opinion. FDD is prerequisite for sophisticated PE transactions.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD team produces a ''Quality of Earnings'' (QofE) report. What core analyses does this typically contain?', '["Only revenue review","(1) Trailing twelve-month (TTM) EBITDA analysis; (2) Adjustments review (one-time items, normalisations); (3) Revenue recognition testing; (4) Cost classification review; (5) Related party transactions; (6) Management accounts reconciliation; (7) Run-rate analysis; (8) Sustainable earnings view","Only expenses","Random analysis"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Quality of Earnings (QofE) report components: (1) TTM EBITDA analysis: period-by-period trending with variance explanations; (2) Adjustments review: validates management''s adjustments, identifies additional normalisations; (3) Revenue recognition testing: timing, cutoffs, accounting policies, channel stuffing; (4) Cost classification: operating vs. non-operating, one-time vs. recurring; (5) Related party transactions: economic substance, pricing normalisation; (6) Management accounts reconciliation: tie to audit, identify differences; (7) Run-rate analysis: future sustainable EBITDA; (8) Seasonal/cyclical normalisation. Output: (1) Buyer-adjusted EBITDA view; (2) Gap to seller''s presentation; (3) Recommended EBITDA for valuation; (4) Risk factors identified; (5) Post-close considerations. QofE typically produces 50-200 page report depending on deal complexity.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies €4M of ''management adjustments'' excluded from EBITDA. How is each evaluated?', '["Accept all","Rigorous evaluation: (1) Is the item truly one-time or non-recurring?; (2) Quantification validated?; (3) Will it reoccur in buyer''s hands?; (4) Is it disguising ongoing costs?; (5) Documentation supports adjustment?; each adjustment validated specifically, not accepted in bulk","Reject all","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Management adjustment evaluation: (1) One-time vs. recurring: truly exceptional events vs. ongoing cost disguised; (2) Quantification: is amount supported by documentation?; (3) Buyer-specific: will adjustment persist for PE buyer?; (4) Transparency: is the adjustment disclosed or hidden?; (5) Trend analysis: does the item appear every year (indicating recurring)?; (6) Business context: does adjustment make operational sense?. Valid adjustments: (1) Completed facility consolidation with documented savings; (2) Owner-related expenses that will cease; (3) Non-recurring legal settlements; (4) Transaction-specific costs; (5) Completed restructuring programs. Invalid adjustments: (1) Annual ''restructuring'' costs; (2) Ongoing compliance costs called one-time; (3) Projected (not realised) savings; (4) Management salaries called excessive; (5) Normal operating variability.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD normalises ''working capital'' as part of the SPA. What does ''normalised'' mean?', '["Average working capital","Working capital level that reflects normal operating conditions, typically: (1) 12-24 month average of historical; (2) Adjusted for non-recurring items; (3) Reflective of business steady-state; (4) Agreed between buyer and seller; (5) Protects buyer from seller manipulation","Random amount","Always €0"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Normalised working capital in SPA: (1) Purpose: reflect ''normal'' operating WC, not seller''s manipulated position at closing; (2) Methodology: calculate 12-24 month average of actual WC; (3) Adjustments: remove non-recurring items (one-time inventory buildup, unusual AR spike); (4) Normalisation: reflects sustainable WC given current business scale; (5) Agreement: buyer and seller agree on ''target'' WC in SPA; (6) Closing mechanism: actual WC at closing vs. target, price adjusted for difference. Example: (1) 12-month average WC: €25M; (2) Adjusted for one-time items: €23M; (3) SPA target: €23M; (4) Closing actual: €20M; (5) Price adjustment: reduce purchase price by €3M (shortfall below target). Protection: (1) Prevents pre-sale manipulation; (2) Ensures buyer receives ''normal'' business; (3) Aligns parties on operating expectations.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''debt-like items'' in the target''s balance sheet. Examples include:', '["Only bank debt","Multiple types: (1) Pension deficits; (2) Tax payables (uncontested); (3) Contingent liabilities; (4) Earnouts from prior acquisitions; (5) Operating lease liabilities (post-IFRS 16); (6) Deferred compensation; (7) Uncashed dividends; (8) Provisions for onerous contracts","Random items","Only trade payables"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Debt-like items (DLI) - items treated as debt in EV bridge: (1) Pension deficits: unfunded obligations to retirees; (2) Tax payables: uncontested taxes owed; (3) Contingent liabilities: warranty claims, guarantees, litigation provisions; (4) Earnouts from prior acquisitions: remaining purchase consideration; (5) Operating lease liabilities (IFRS 16): future lease commitments; (6) Deferred compensation: management incentive obligations; (7) Provisions: onerous contracts, environmental obligations, warranty reserves; (8) Customer deposits/advances (sometimes); (9) Related party loans. Treatment: (1) Added to debt in EV bridge; (2) Deducted from equity value; (3) Affects pricing negotiation; (4) Buyer assumes or requires settlement. Sophisticated FDD teams identify DLI that seller may exclude; typical findings can be €5-20M on mid-market deals.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD examines ''revenue recognition'' practices. What issues might be flagged?', '["Random issues","Common concerns: (1) Revenue recognised before services delivered (bill-and-hold, consignment); (2) Percentage-of-completion manipulation; (3) Side agreements altering terms; (4) Channel stuffing; (5) Renewal/extension policy changes; (6) Contract modifications; (7) Aggressive interpretation of accounting standards","Only fraud","Only timing"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Revenue recognition red flags in FDD: (1) Bill-and-hold: revenue recognised before shipment; tests include risk transfer verification; (2) Consignment: recognised when inventory moves to distributor, not when sold to end customer; (3) Percentage-of-completion: accelerated revenue in long-term contracts; (4) Side agreements: unofficial terms that alter revenue (return privileges, payment terms); (5) Channel stuffing: inventory pushed to distributors at period-end; (6) Renewal policies: changes in how renewals counted; (7) Contract modifications: aggressive treatment of amendments; (8) Round-tripping: selling and repurchasing. FDD testing: (1) Contract review — sample significant contracts; (2) Cut-off testing — year-end revenue timing; (3) Customer confirmations — verify receipt; (4) Return analysis — post-period returns; (5) Channel inventory — distributor stock levels; (6) Trend analysis — unusual patterns. Red flags trigger deeper investigation.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD analyses cost classification. They identify €2M of ''selling expenses'' classified as ''cost of goods sold.'' What''s the impact?', '["No impact","Classification affects gross margin, opex, and key ratios: (1) €2M shifted decreases GM by 2pp (on €100M revenue); (2) Increases opex by 2pp; (3) Affects EBITDA: unchanged if both are operating; (4) Changes peer comparisons; (5) Shouldn''t affect total EBITDA, but affects operational metrics","Only revenue","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Cost classification impact analysis: (1) COGS vs. Opex: economically same (both operating expenses), but affects ratios differently; (2) €2M shifted from Opex to COGS: (a) Gross margin decreases by 2%; (b) Operating expense ratio decreases; (c) EBITDA unchanged (both are operating costs); (3) Peer comparison issues: if peers classify similarly, ratios compare correctly; if not, direct comparison misleads; (4) Industry norms: (a) Some industries recognise selling costs as COGS (where directly allocated); (b) Others classify in Opex; (5) Key question: is classification consistent with industry norms? Aggressive classification: moving costs to improve key metrics (gross margin often primary target). Analysis: (1) Industry benchmarking; (2) Peer comparison; (3) Historical consistency; (4) Management rationale; (5) Impact on operational metrics.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD reviews ''related party transactions.'' The target pays €3M annually to a property company owned by the founder. How is this treated?', '["Accept as legitimate","Investigate: (1) Market-based rent comparison; (2) Terms of lease (arm''s length?); (3) Impact on EBITDA (may be above or below market); (4) Post-transaction arrangement (will it continue?); (5) Normalise if below or above market; (6) Include in SPA representations","Reject","Random treatment"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Related party transaction analysis: (1) Current payment: €3M annual rent; (2) Benchmark analysis: what would similar property rent for externally? (comparison to market rates); (3) If below market (e.g., €1.5M): target is subsidising — normalise EBITDA down by difference; (4) If above market (e.g., €4M): inflating expenses — adjust up, seller extracting excess; (5) Post-transaction: must clarify if relationship continues (ownership change may affect); (6) SPA considerations: (a) Representations about related parties; (b) Post-closing relationships; (c) Transition services agreements. Common related party transactions: (1) Rent to owner-controlled entities; (2) Consulting fees to family members; (3) Above-market salaries; (4) Service contracts with affiliates; (5) Loans with non-market terms. Sophisticated FDD normalises all to market-equivalent to understand true operating economics.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD analyses the target''s ''management accounts'' against the audited financial statements. What discrepancies warrant investigation?', '["Accept audit only","Investigate: (1) Material differences; (2) Classification differences; (3) Timing differences; (4) Reconciliation approach; (5) Audit adjustments pattern; (6) Management reporting quality; systematic differences may indicate controls issues or earnings management","Accept management only","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Management accounts vs. audit reconciliation: (1) Material differences: amounts >5% of EBITDA warrant investigation; (2) Classification differences: how items categorised may differ; (3) Timing: month-end cutoff differences; (4) Reconciliation: typical process — monthly management accounts reconciled to audit at year-end; (5) Audit adjustments pattern: significant audit adjustments annually suggest weak controls. Investigations include: (1) What drove the difference? (classification, timing, accounting choice); (2) Was audit correct? (typically yes, unless audit quality concerns); (3) Does management have different view? (sophisticated accounting vs. errors); (4) Are controls adequate to produce reliable data? Implications: (1) Reliability of financials for valuation; (2) Post-close controls strengthening; (3) Management team capability assessment; (4) Risk factors. Well-managed companies have clean reconciliations; problematic ones have frequent adjustments.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD validates management''s ''financial projections.'' What comprehensive approach is typical?', '["Accept projections","Multi-dimensional validation: (1) Historical trend analysis; (2) Bottom-up validation (revenue by customer/product); (3) Assumption testing; (4) Sensitivity analysis; (5) Comparable company benchmarking; (6) Management track record; (7) Industry growth rates; (8) Scenario analysis; rigorous reality check","Random testing","Only historical"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Financial projection validation: (1) Historical trend analysis: is projection consistent with 3-year trajectory?; (2) Bottom-up: build revenue by customer/product — can it be achieved?; (3) Assumption testing: key drivers validated (growth, margin, capex); (4) Sensitivity analysis: impact of changing key variables; (5) Comparable benchmarking: peer growth rates, margin trends; (6) Management track record: have they delivered past projections?; (7) Industry growth: is projection aligned with market; (8) Scenario analysis: base, upside, downside scenarios; (9) Root cause analysis: what drives delta between historical and projected?. FDD typical findings: (1) Projections slightly optimistic (most common); (2) Hockey stick growth assumptions; (3) Margin improvement assumptions; (4) Working capital assumptions aggressive. Adjustment: FDD typically produces ''realistic'' projections that may be 5-15% below management''s aspirational case.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies the target''s ''budget vs. actual'' performance. Historical achievement: 85% of budget. What does this suggest?', '["Exceeds expectations","Below-budget achievement indicates: (1) Aspirational budgeting (pattern of missing); (2) Management overcommits in projections; (3) Actual performance more reliable indicator than budget; (4) PE due diligence should: apply haircut to current projections; validate against historical achievement rate","Random","Pure performance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Budget vs. actual analysis: (1) 85% achievement: chronic below-budget pattern; (2) Interpretation: management tends to overcommit; (3) For projection validation: apply 15% haircut to current projections for baseline case; (4) Comparison to best-in-class: companies achieve 95-105% of budget consistently. Implications: (1) Management projection credibility reduced; (2) Valuation: use conservative projections; (3) Investment thesis: acknowledge execution risk; (4) Post-close: new budget discipline, performance management; (5) Incentive structures: tied to realistic metrics. PE response: (1) Build model with historical achievement rate; (2) Consider management replacement if chronic underperformance; (3) Improve forecasting processes; (4) Implement budget rigor. Reliable forecasting is a capability that must be developed; pattern of underperformance is a risk factor.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD reviews the target''s ''inventory'' for quality. Aging analysis shows 25% of inventory >180 days old. What analysis follows?', '["Ignore aging","Investigate: (1) Obsolescence provisions adequate; (2) Markdown exposure; (3) Sell-through rate analysis; (4) Write-down required at closing; (5) Inventory turnover trend; (6) Industry comparison; (7) Impact on working capital normalisation; (8) Potential EBITDA adjustment","Random","Only size"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Inventory aging analysis: (1) 25% inventory >180 days: high — potentially obsolete or slow-moving; (2) Obsolescence provisions: are reserves adequate?; (3) Industry benchmark: target 5-15% typically acceptable; 25% is red flag; (4) Analysis required: (a) Age brackets (0-30, 31-90, 91-180, >180 days); (b) Sell-through rates by age; (c) Recent write-downs; (d) Customer contracts with old inventory; (e) Obsolescence provisions relative to aged inventory. PE implications: (1) Pre-closing write-down may be required: €Xm; (2) EBITDA normalization: if inventory has been slow-moving for years, reported EBITDA may be overstated; (3) Working capital normalisation: target should be adjusted downward for ''normal'' inventory level; (4) Post-closing: inventory optimization program, potential write-downs. Inventory issues often discovered in FDD; affects pricing and post-closing actions.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies the target''s ''deferred revenue'' liability grew 40% over 2 years. What does this suggest?', '["Accounting error","Growing deferred revenue indicates: (1) Increasing prepayment from customers; (2) Business model shift toward subscription; (3) Strong customer commitment; (4) Future revenue visibility; (5) Favorable cash flow dynamics; (6) Could enhance valuation; but: (1) Accounting policy changes; (2) Customer concentration; require investigation","Negative trend","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Deferred revenue analysis: (1) Growing deferred revenue: customers paying upfront for future services; (2) Positive implications: (a) Business model strength (customers commit); (b) Cash flow advantages (receive payment before service); (c) Revenue visibility (committed future revenue); (d) Higher valuations (recurring revenue multiplier); (3) Validate: (a) Contract terms — genuine prepayment vs. accounting treatment; (b) Customer base — concentrated or diversified prepayment; (c) Accounting policy consistency — no changes inflating balance; (d) Product/service quality — customers willing to prepay. PE thesis: (1) Subscription business model typically prefers premium; (2) Deferred revenue supports LBO thesis; (3) Working capital calculation: treat as non-debt-like item; (4) Enterprise value bridge: exclude from debt-like items. Deferred revenue growth signals business model strength — a positive indicator requiring validation.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD examines ''accounts receivable'' quality. Target has €25M AR with 50% over 60 days past due. What concerns does this raise?', '["Excellent collection","Significant concerns: (1) Collection risk: high proportion past due indicates payment issues; (2) Bad debt exposure: €12.5M may be uncollectable; (3) Business quality concern: customers not paying on time; (4) Working capital normalisation: AR may need adjustment; (5) EBITDA impact if write-downs required","Random age","Healthy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Accounts receivable aging analysis: (1) 50% AR >60 days past due: extremely concerning; (2) Healthy businesses: typically <20% of AR past due; (3) Aging brackets: 0-30 days (acceptable), 31-60 (investigate), 61-90 (concerning), 91+ (bad debt risk). Analyses required: (1) Bad debt reserves: adequate for exposure?; (2) Customer payment history: pattern analysis; (3) Customer financial health: can they pay?; (4) Contract terms: payment terms fair?; (5) Collection processes: adequate? (6) Historical write-offs: level and trend. Implications: (1) Potential write-downs needed; (2) Working capital overstated; (3) Revenue quality concerns; (4) Business model issues (customers unhappy, disputes, or financial distress); (5) Pricing negotiations. PE response: (1) Price adjustment for AR quality; (2) Cash collection program; (3) Customer relationship improvement; (4) Working capital discipline. Critical FDD finding.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD reviews the target''s ''financial controls.'' They find monthly close takes 25 days post-period. What does this reveal?', '["Efficient process","Weak controls: (1) Industry best-in-class: 3-5 days; (2) 25 days indicates: complex process, manual work, weak technology, staffing issues; (3) Risks: outdated financial information, weak decision-making, errors in reporting; (4) Post-closing action: finance transformation required","Random","Best practice"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Monthly close timeline analysis: (1) Best-in-class: 3-5 days; (2) Average: 10-15 days; (3) Poor: 20-30+ days; (4) 25 days is very slow; (5) Indicators of weak controls. Root causes: (1) Manual processes: spreadsheet-dependent; (2) ERP/accounting technology gaps; (3) Inadequate staffing; (4) Complex organisation structure; (5) Multiple systems/integrations; (6) Year-end-only closing discipline; (7) Weak subsidiary reporting. Implications: (1) Outdated management information; (2) Weak decision-making; (3) Error risk in reporting; (4) Poor tax optimization opportunity; (5) Compliance risk. Post-closing PE actions: (1) Finance transformation: implement monthly close acceleration; (2) Technology investment: automation, integration; (3) Staffing evaluation; (4) Process reengineering; (5) Target: reduce to 5-7 days within 12 months. Typical PE value creation lever.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''off-balance-sheet'' arrangements. Examples include:', '["Only public debt","Multiple items: (1) Operating leases (pre-IFRS 16); (2) Synthetic leases; (3) Guarantees for affiliated entities; (4) Letters of credit; (5) Supplier financing arrangements; (6) Factoring/securitisation; (7) Joint venture commitments; (8) Contingent liabilities not recognised","Random","None"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Off-balance-sheet (OBS) arrangements: (1) Operating leases (if pre-IFRS 16 treatment applicable): lease commitments for property, equipment; significant amounts may exist; (2) Synthetic leases: lease arrangements designed to keep debt off balance sheet; (3) Guarantees: target guaranteeing obligations of affiliated entities; (4) Letters of credit: contingent obligations to pay if conditions met; (5) Supplier financing: extended payment terms creating unseen obligations; (6) Factoring/securitisation: selling AR to get cash but with recourse; (7) Joint venture commitments: capital contribution requirements; (8) Environmental obligations: contingent but material. FDD must: (1) Review all contracts and commitments; (2) Identify off-balance-sheet items; (3) Quantify impact; (4) Assess risk of crystallisation; (5) Include in SPA representations; (6) Consider in EV bridge as debt-like. Hidden OBS items can materially affect deal economics.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD analyses the target''s ''tax compliance.'' What areas receive focus?', '["Only past taxes","Comprehensive review: (1) Tax positions (aggressive vs. defensible); (2) Transfer pricing arrangements; (3) Uncertain tax positions (UTPs); (4) Recent audits and controversies; (5) Jurisdictions and related risks; (6) Permanent differences and deferred taxes; (7) Net operating losses utilization; (8) Recent tax law changes","Random","Only US taxes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Tax DD scope: (1) Tax positions: aggressive or defensible on major issues?; (2) Transfer pricing: intercompany transactions priced appropriately?; (3) Uncertain tax positions (UTPs): identified, quantified, and disclosed?; (4) Recent audits: findings, settlements, outstanding items; (5) Jurisdictions: tax exposure by country/state; (6) Permanent differences: tax provisions reflecting economic reality?; (7) Net operating losses (NOLs): available and restricted in post-transaction; (8) Recent tax law changes: impact on target?. Areas of concern: (1) Pending audits; (2) Large UTPs indicating dispute risk; (3) Aggressive transfer pricing; (4) Unrecorded liabilities; (5) Withholding tax exposure on cross-border. Output: (1) Tax liability estimate (including UTPs); (2) Tax structuring recommendations; (3) Risk quantification; (4) SPA tax indemnities; (5) Post-closing planning. Tax DD often conducted by specialist (e.g., Big Four tax teams).'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''segment reporting'' issues. The target has 3 segments but consolidated EBITDA. Why is segment reporting important?', '["Ignore segments","Segment reporting reveals: (1) Profitability by business line; (2) Growth rates by segment; (3) Cost allocation methodology; (4) Segment interdependencies; (5) Carve-out complexity; (6) Individual segment valuation; critical for sum-of-parts analysis and operational understanding","Only revenue","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Segment reporting importance: (1) Profitability per segment: some segments subsidising others; (2) Growth trajectories: different segments growing at different rates; (3) Cost allocations: how shared costs attributed to segments; (4) Interdependencies: customer overlap, operational integration; (5) Individual performance: identify winners and losers; (6) Sum-of-parts valuation: each segment at appropriate multiple. Analysis approach: (1) Segment-level P&L reconstruction; (2) Cost allocation methodology; (3) Transfer pricing between segments; (4) Customer concentration by segment; (5) Growth vs. investment balance; (6) Segment-specific risks. PE implications: (1) Portfolio analysis: consider keeping/divesting segments; (2) Valuation multiples differ by segment; (3) Investment allocation: focus on high-return segments; (4) Exit options: sell individual segments or as bundle. Comprehensive segment analysis often reveals opportunities not apparent in consolidated view.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD reviews ''capital expenditure'' history and projections. Historical capex average 4% of revenue; projection shows 3% going forward. What''s the analysis?', '["Accept","Investigate: (1) Is 3% realistic or underfunding?; (2) Historical maintenance vs. growth breakdown; (3) Industry benchmark (3-5% typical?); (4) Replacement cycle (deferred capex bills coming); (5) Technology upgrade needs; (6) Competitive requirements; (7) Normalisation for realistic level","Random","Reject"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Capital expenditure analysis: (1) Historical: 4% average; (2) Projected: 3%; (3) Reduction: 25% decrease; (4) Questions: Why declining? Is 3% sustainable? Is 4% historical inflated?. Investigation: (1) Capex composition: maintenance vs. growth split historically; (2) Asset age: older assets may need more capex, not less; (3) Technology obsolescence: new technology requirements; (4) Industry benchmarks: typical capex for peer group; (5) Deferred capex: any past years underinvested catching up?; (6) Specific planned projects: decommissioning or postponing?; (7) Competitive position: can target operate with less capex?. Implications: (1) If 3% underfunding, future issues; (2) If 3% realistic, favorable for valuation; (3) FCF impact: difference is €1% × revenue = meaningful; (4) Long-term sustainability concerns. FDD typically validates with: industry analysis, management discussions, asset audits, comparable company analysis.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD examines the target''s ''audit quality.'' What factors indicate audit quality?', '["Only audit fee","Multiple factors: (1) Audit firm (Big 4 vs. mid-tier); (2) Audit partner experience in sector; (3) Auditor tenure (rotation); (4) Unqualified opinions in recent years; (5) Material weaknesses disclosed; (6) Auditor-client relationships (independence); (7) Pattern of audit adjustments; (8) Emphasis of matter paragraphs","Random","Only fee"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Audit quality indicators: (1) Audit firm: Big 4 (Deloitte, EY, KPMG, PwC) typically higher quality than mid-tier (Grant Thornton, RSM, BDO) but exceptions exist; (2) Audit partner: experience in target''s industry matters; (3) Tenure: auditor rotation (typically 7-10 years max) maintains independence; (4) Opinion history: unqualified (''clean'') opinions across recent years; (5) Material weaknesses: none disclosed is positive; any identified need investigation; (6) Independence: pattern of consulting services can compromise independence; (7) Audit adjustments: magnitude and frequency reveal control effectiveness; (8) Emphasis paragraphs: substantive audit concerns highlighted; (9) Management letter: internal audit findings. Post-transaction: (1) Decide on audit firm retention or change; (2) Enhance audit committee; (3) Strengthen controls environment; (4) Improve reporting systems; (5) Investment in financial reporting quality.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''restructuring costs'' in three consecutive years. How is this treated?', '["Accept as one-time","Treat as ongoing cost: (1) Recurring ''restructuring'' indicates chronic transformation; (2) Not truly one-time despite labeling; (3) Include in normalised EBITDA; (4) Question management credibility; (5) Post-closing: address underlying issues driving continued restructuring","Exclude always","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Recurring ''restructuring costs'' analysis: (1) Three consecutive years: not one-time by definition; (2) Pattern suggests: chronic transformation needs, management restructuring churn, ongoing operational issues; (3) Proper treatment: include in operating EBITDA; (4) Implications: (a) Management sophistication concern: why does restructuring keep happening?; (b) Business issues underneath; (c) EBITDA quality lower than reported (normalised). FDD adjustment: (1) Add back restructuring to EBITDA if management excluded; (2) Quantify recurring level; (3) Document pattern for IC review; (4) Factor into valuation. PE response: (1) Investigate root causes; (2) Develop transformation plan addressing structural issues; (3) Build operational stability; (4) Reduce ongoing restructuring over hold period; (5) Management accountability. ''Restructuring'' becomes legitimate one-time only with: (1) Clear endpoint; (2) Measurable outcome; (3) Non-recurring nature validated; (4) Not being repeated next year.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD examines the target''s ''management reporting package.'' What does quality look like?', '["Random format","High-quality package includes: (1) Monthly P&L vs. budget/prior year; (2) Balance sheet changes; (3) Cash flow statement; (4) KPI dashboard; (5) Segment reporting; (6) Customer/product analysis; (7) Variance explanations; (8) Forward look; (9) Operational metrics; (10) Capital allocation tracking","Only financials","Only one page"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Management reporting package quality criteria: (1) Comprehensive P&L: monthly, YTD, prior year, budget comparisons; (2) Balance sheet: material changes explained; (3) Cash flow statement: operating, investing, financing; (4) KPI dashboard: operational metrics beyond financials; (5) Segment reporting: business line performance; (6) Customer analysis: top customers, concentration, retention; (7) Product analysis: performance by product/service; (8) Variance explanations: significant deviations explained; (9) Forward look: outlook for coming quarter/year; (10) Operational metrics: utilisation, efficiency, productivity; (11) Capital allocation: capex, acquisitions, debt paydown tracking. Quality indicators: (1) Timeliness (fast close); (2) Accuracy (reconciled to audit); (3) Transparency (honest reporting); (4) Forward-looking; (5) Actionable insights. PE assesses: (1) Current management reporting; (2) Gaps to improve; (3) Technology investments needed; (4) Team capability. Critical capability for PE value creation.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD reviews ''pension obligations'' of the target. Defined benefit plan shows €15M deficit. How is this handled?', '["Ignore","Multiple considerations: (1) Quantify exactly (actuarial valuation); (2) Funding requirements timeline; (3) Risk of deficit growth (market volatility, demographics); (4) Treatment as debt-like item in EV bridge; (5) SPA representations; (6) Potential settlement or transfer strategies","Random","Only size"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pension deficit DD analysis: (1) Current deficit: €15M at latest valuation; (2) Underlying assumptions: discount rate, expected return, longevity; (3) Sensitivity: impact of rate/return changes; (4) Funding requirements: timing of contributions; (5) Future growth risk: if assumptions change adversely; (6) Settlement strategies: plan freeze, buy-out, transfer to insurer. EV bridge treatment: (1) Deficit is debt-like item; (2) Subtract from EV to derive equity value; (3) Price negotiation: account for uncertainty; (4) Protection: SPA representations on pension; funding. Post-closing actions: (1) Plan review with actuary; (2) Funding strategy; (3) Employee communication; (4) Potential restructuring of plan; (5) Insurance/buy-out options; (6) Long-term de-risking. For PE: (1) Pension deficit reduces equity value; (2) Ongoing obligation management required; (3) Can be opportunity to reshape benefit structure. Material factor in mid-market and large deals.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''customer contracts'' requiring detailed review. What specific aspects warrant examination?', '["Random review","Comprehensive analysis: (1) Contract terms and duration; (2) Pricing mechanisms and escalation; (3) Change of control provisions; (4) Termination rights; (5) Performance obligations; (6) Warranty/liability provisions; (7) Payment terms; (8) Exclusivity; (9) Renewal options; (10) Auto-termination clauses","Only price","Only revenue"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Customer contract review focus: (1) Terms and duration: contract length, renewal clauses; (2) Pricing: mechanisms (fixed, escalating, indexed), pricing power; (3) Change of control: triggered by acquisition? requires consent? allows termination?; (4) Termination: conditions for either party to terminate; (5) Performance obligations: SLAs, delivery commitments; (6) Warranty/liability: exposure from contract performance; (7) Payment terms: credit risk, working capital; (8) Exclusivity: target''s rights to compete; (9) Renewal options: guaranteed or discretionary; (10) Auto-termination: provisions that could trigger unexpectedly. Red flags: (1) Change of control provisions requiring consent; (2) Short remaining terms near exit; (3) Unfavorable termination rights; (4) Aggressive warranty/indemnity exposure; (5) Pricing lock at unfavorable levels; (6) Exclusivity limiting growth. Material contracts identified early; consent processes planned; valuation adjustments made accordingly.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD examines the target''s ''IT systems for finance.'' What indicates financial system weakness?', '["Random assessment","Warning signs: (1) Multiple disconnected systems; (2) Heavy spreadsheet reliance; (3) Manual reconciliations; (4) Weak integration between GL, operations, commercial; (5) Limited reporting capabilities; (6) Outdated technology; (7) Customisation-dependent; (8) Single key person risk","Only age","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Financial IT weakness indicators: (1) Disconnected systems: separate GL, operational, commercial systems requiring manual bridging; (2) Spreadsheet reliance: critical calculations in Excel rather than systems; (3) Manual reconciliations: time-consuming, error-prone; (4) Weak integration: sales to finance, operations to accounting gaps; (5) Limited reporting: can''t produce needed management information; (6) Outdated technology: old versions, poor user interfaces, unsupported; (7) Customisation dependence: hard-coded processes that are inflexible; (8) Single person knowledge: key employee with undocumented expertise. Implications: (1) Error risk in financial reporting; (2) Weak decision-making (slow, incomplete information); (3) Compliance risk; (4) Growth constraint (can''t scale). Post-closing PE actions: (1) Financial IT assessment; (2) ERP modernization roadmap; (3) Integration improvement; (4) Reporting enhancement; (5) Talent investment. Typical capex: €2-10M over 12-24 months depending on size.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''cost structure'' issues. Fixed costs are 70% of total; industry average is 55%. What does this mean?', '["Efficient","High fixed cost exposure: (1) Less flexibility in downturns; (2) Margin volatility with volume changes; (3) Higher operational leverage (good upside, bad downside); (4) Competitive pressure in weak markets; (5) Less ability to manage costs; (6) Higher exit multiples vulnerability if growth slows","Random","Always good"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Fixed cost structure analysis: (1) 70% fixed vs 55% industry average; (2) Difference: 15 percentage points higher fixed exposure; (3) Operational leverage implications: (a) Amplified profitability when volume grows (upside); (b) Margin compression when volume declines (downside); (c) Less agility to manage costs. In downturns: (1) Revenue decline causes disproportionate EBITDA decline; (2) Margin compression significant; (3) Difficult to reduce fixed costs quickly; (4) Competitive position weakens (can''t compete on price during downturn). Analysis: (1) Fixed cost breakdown (labor, rent, depreciation, other); (2) Variable cost ratio; (3) Scenario analysis with volume changes; (4) Capacity utilisation; (5) Cost flexibility. PE strategies: (1) Cost flexibility programs (variable labor, outsourcing); (2) Revenue stabilization (long-term contracts); (3) Operational hedges; (4) Cyclical adjustment of leverage. Higher fixed cost base requires lower leverage and more conservative analysis.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD analyses ''foreign currency'' exposures. Target operates in 5 countries with 60% revenue outside home currency. What analysis is needed?', '["Ignore FX","Comprehensive FX analysis: (1) Currency exposure by country; (2) Natural hedges (cost vs. revenue match); (3) Hedging policy; (4) Translation vs. transaction exposure; (5) Historical FX volatility impact; (6) Pricing power to pass through FX; (7) Financial statement translation effects; (8) Sensitivity analysis","Random","Only home currency"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Foreign currency exposure DD: (1) Currency mix: 60% foreign reveals significant exposure; (2) Exposure types: (a) Transaction (invoices in foreign currency); (b) Translation (subsidiary financials in home currency); (c) Economic (competitive position from FX); (3) Natural hedges: revenue in currency matched by costs? Local operations effective hedges; (4) Hedging policy: what % of exposure hedged? What instruments?; (5) Historical impact: how has FX affected reported results?; (6) Pricing pass-through: can pricing absorb FX movements?; (7) Sensitivity: scenarios for 10-20% FX changes; (8) Asset/liability positions: foreign subsidiary equity exposure. Implications: (1) Reported earnings volatility from FX; (2) Working capital requirements affected; (3) Valuation considerations (DCF in multiple currencies); (4) Hedging costs; (5) Competitive positioning in downturns. PE FDD: (1) Quantify FX exposure; (2) Validate hedging; (3) Model FX scenarios; (4) Price reflects FX risk.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''customer dependence'' issues. Top customer represents 40% of revenue. What additional FDD analysis is needed?', '["Ignore concentration","Customer-specific FDD: (1) Customer financial health (can they pay?); (2) Relationship strength (length, contract terms); (3) Recent payment history; (4) Industry dynamics affecting customer; (5) Potential alternatives for target; (6) Contract risk (termination, change of control); (7) Pricing and margin details","Only size","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Customer concentration FDD: (1) 40% from single customer: significant concentration; (2) Customer financial health: credit rating, payment history, industry condition, recent performance; (3) Relationship strength: duration (e.g., 10+ years), contract depth, integration; (4) Payment history: timely payments, disputes; (5) Customer''s own customer dynamics: is their business thriving?; (6) Alternatives: what if customer exits? Are there replacements?; (7) Contract risk: change of control, termination rights, renewal terms; (8) Pricing dynamics: at-market pricing or concessions; (9) Relationship dependencies: specific products, services, geography. Red flags: (1) Customer in declining industry; (2) Recent contract renegotiation unfavorable; (3) Relationship relationship-dependent individual; (4) Alternative suppliers available; (5) Pricing pressure. PE response: (1) Full customer diligence; (2) Stress scenarios (customer loss); (3) Contract review for protective provisions; (4) Price reflects concentration risk; (5) Post-close diversification strategy.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD examines the target''s ''budget process.'' What processes indicate good budget discipline?', '["Only annual budget","Strong process: (1) Annual detailed budget by department/segment; (2) Monthly vs. budget variance analysis; (3) Formal quarterly forecast updates; (4) Bottom-up and top-down reconciliation; (5) Executive review and approval; (6) Variance accountability; (7) Budget used for decision-making","Random","No budget needed"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Strong budget process indicators: (1) Annual budget: detailed by department/segment/product; (2) Monthly variance analysis: actual vs. budget with explanations; (3) Quarterly forecast updates: acknowledge changes; (4) Bottom-up/top-down reconciliation: ground-level detail meets executive vision; (5) Executive review and approval: governance layer; (6) Variance accountability: managers responsible for their budgets; (7) Budget used for decision-making: investment decisions, hiring, pricing; (8) Performance tied to budget achievement. Weak process indicators: (1) Budget prepared only annually without updates; (2) No variance analysis or explanations; (3) No consequence for missing budget; (4) Budget disconnected from operations; (5) Short time horizons only; (6) Top-down without ground-level input. PE FDD assesses: (1) Current process quality; (2) Technology supporting; (3) Management capability; (4) Post-close improvements needed. Strong budget discipline enables PE value creation through performance management.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD reviews ''capital allocation'' decisions. What patterns indicate management discipline?', '["Random","Disciplined patterns: (1) ROIC analysis for capex decisions; (2) Hurdle rates for investments; (3) M&A discipline (not deal-mania); (4) Share buybacks at value-creating levels; (5) Debt paydown when appropriate; (6) Dividend policy alignment; (7) Consistent strategy over time","Only M&A","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Capital allocation discipline indicators: (1) Capex: ROIC-based decision framework, hurdle rates, post-completion reviews; (2) M&A: strategic rationale, valuation discipline, integration success rate; (3) Share buybacks: timing (price-based), opportunistic; (4) Debt paydown: leverage management, opportunistic refinancing; (5) Dividends: sustainable, policy-based; (6) R&D: growth investment or maintenance; (7) Consistency: strategic direction maintained over time; (8) Returns: track record of capital generating returns. Strong patterns: (1) ROIC consistently exceeds cost of capital; (2) M&A contributes to value (not destroying); (3) Buybacks support per-share value; (4) Debt managed to optimize structure; (5) Strategic consistency. Weak patterns: (1) Capex without return analysis; (2) M&A with poor success rate; (3) Value-destroying buybacks; (4) Excessive leverage without benefit. PE assessment: (1) Historical capital allocation track record; (2) Future opportunity quality; (3) Management capability for value-creating allocation.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''transfer pricing'' issues with cross-border operations. What are typical concerns?', '["Ignore","Concerns: (1) Prices between subsidiaries at arm''s length?; (2) Profit allocation across jurisdictions; (3) Tax authorities disputing pricing; (4) Transfer pricing documentation adequate; (5) Advance pricing agreements (APAs) in place; (6) Post-transaction planning implications","Random","Only taxes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Transfer pricing DD: (1) Arm''s length principle: transactions between subsidiaries should be priced as if between unrelated parties; (2) Profit allocation: artificial concentration in low-tax jurisdictions; (3) Tax authority disputes: history and current status; (4) Documentation: comprehensive TP study required (OECD guidelines); (5) APAs: pre-agreements with tax authorities on pricing; (6) Country-by-country reporting: multi-jurisdictional transparency. Red flags: (1) Significant intercompany pricing without arm''s length support; (2) Profit concentration in low-tax jurisdictions; (3) Active transfer pricing disputes; (4) Missing documentation; (5) Rapid changes in TP approach; (6) Customer-supplier relationships concentrated internationally. For PE: (1) Quantify exposure (potential tax liability if authorities challenge); (2) SPA representations for tax compliance; (3) Indemnities for pre-closing tax risks; (4) Post-closing TP review and adjustment; (5) Tax-efficient structure. Transfer pricing issues can be multi-hundred million dollar exposures in large multinational targets.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD reviews ''working capital'' history. Historical WC averaged €25M; latest year €35M. What drove the growth?', '["Random growth","Analyse components: (1) AR grew? (slower collections or revenue growth?); (2) Inventory grew? (sales decline or production increase?); (3) AP stable/declining? (payment timing changes?); (4) Seasonal or structural?; (5) Revenue growth vs. WC growth correlation; (6) Normalisation implications; understand fundamental vs. timing","Always good","Always bad"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Working capital growth analysis: (1) €10M growth (40% increase) needs explanation; (2) Component breakdown: (a) AR growth — slower payment collection or just revenue growth?; (b) Inventory growth — poor inventory turns or strategic buildup?; (c) AP trends — paying faster or negotiating longer terms?; (3) Root cause analysis: (a) Underlying business change; (b) Operational improvement needed; (c) Seasonal timing; (d) Strategic decisions (customer terms, supplier relationships). Common causes: (1) Revenue growth: 40% WC growth on stable revenue = problematic; 40% WC growth on 40% revenue growth = proportional; (2) Operational issues: weak collections, inventory management; (3) Customer mix: larger enterprise customers with longer terms; (4) Supply chain: strategic inventory positioning. For SPA: (1) Set ''normalised'' WC at appropriate level; (2) Protect buyer from unsustainable WC bloat; (3) Allow for legitimate revenue-related growth. Understanding drivers is essential before setting target.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD analyses ''cash flow conversion.'' EBITDA is €50M but operating cash flow is €30M. Why the €20M gap?', '["Random","Gap analysis: (1) Working capital investment €10M; (2) Capex €12M; (3) Cash taxes €5M; (4) Other non-cash items €3M in EBITDA; (5) Total: €30M cash flow from operations; (6) Bridge explains 60% conversion — below strong businesses (80%+)","Accounting error","Fraud"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EBITDA to operating cash flow bridge: (1) EBITDA: €50M; (2) Changes in working capital: -€10M (AR/Inventory growth); (3) Capex: -€12M; (4) Cash taxes: -€5M (despite book tax expense may be different); (5) Other non-cash items: -€3M (stock-based comp, pension, etc.); (6) Operating Cash Flow: €20M? Actually should be EBITDA - capex - cash taxes - WC change (conceptually). Cash Flow Conversion = OCF / EBITDA = 60% (below strong businesses 80%+). Analysis required: (1) Each adjustment explained; (2) Trend over 3 years; (3) Comparison to peers; (4) Legitimate business reasons for gap; (5) Opportunity for improvement. Implications: (1) Below 70% conversion may signal: high capex, aggressive accounting, working capital drain; (2) Valuation adjustment: investors pay more for high cash conversion businesses; (3) Opportunity: PE can improve conversion through operational initiatives. Sophisticated FDD quantifies gap components precisely.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''revenue concentration'' issue. Top 10 customers at 80% of revenue. Post-closing, one top customer gives notice. How does PE handle?', '["Ignore","Contingent outcomes: (1) SPA representations: seller warranted no material customer losses; could be breach; (2) Indemnification claim; (3) Actual loss depends on recoverability; (4) Business plan adjustment needed; (5) Response determines outcome; (6) Strategic customer retention efforts","Random","Accept loss"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Post-closing customer loss handling: (1) SPA review: seller warranted no material customer losses in representations; (2) Breach analysis: does notice trigger a breach?; (3) Indemnification claim: if breach proven, seek damages; (4) Valuation impact: estimate lost EBITDA × multiple; (5) Operational response: (a) Customer retention efforts; (b) Alternative account development; (c) Cost flexibility measures; (6) Business plan adjustment: realistic projections. Process: (1) Legal review: SPA terms, representation accuracy; (2) Evidence gathering: why did customer leave? Signal before closing?; (3) Indemnification: file claim with supporting documentation; (4) Settlement negotiation: typically partial recovery; (5) Operational reality: customer loss happens regardless of SPA outcome. Long-term implications: (1) Customer concentration risk now materialized; (2) Business plan requires revision; (3) Future deals: enhanced DD on customer concentration; (4) Premium for diversified customer bases. PE learning experience that informs future deals.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD analyses the target''s ''earnings quality.'' What indicators suggest high earnings quality?', '["Random","High quality indicators: (1) Strong cash conversion (OCF ≈ EBITDA - capex); (2) Consistent accounting policies; (3) Minimal one-time adjustments; (4) Low management discretion in reporting; (5) Stable revenue patterns; (6) Operating cash flow growing with earnings; (7) Conservative provisioning","Only amount","Only trend"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Earnings quality indicators: (1) Cash conversion: operating cash flow closely matches (or exceeds) EBITDA less capex; conversion >80% indicates high quality; (2) Accounting consistency: same policies applied over time; (3) Minimal adjustments: few non-recurring items; sustainable earnings close to reported; (4) Low management discretion: conservative accounting choices; minimal manipulation of reserves or accruals; (5) Revenue patterns: smooth, recurring, predictable; no unusual spikes; (6) Cash flow growth: correlates with earnings growth; (7) Conservative provisioning: adequate reserves for future obligations. Low quality indicators: (1) Cash flow below EBITDA consistently; (2) Frequent accounting policy changes; (3) Many ''one-time'' adjustments year after year; (4) Aggressive accounting estimates; (5) Volatile revenue patterns; (6) Cash flow diverging from earnings; (7) Insufficient provisioning. PE pays premium for high-quality earnings; applies discounts for low-quality. Critical FDD conclusion affecting deal economics.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''tax structuring'' opportunities pre-acquisition. What examples are typical?', '["No opportunities","Multiple opportunities: (1) Holding company structures; (2) Acquisition entity structure; (3) Interest deductibility optimization; (4) Tax loss utilisation; (5) Jurisdiction selection; (6) Step-up in asset basis; (7) Post-transaction planning alignment","Random","Only tax avoidance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Tax structuring opportunities in PE transactions: (1) Holding company: Luxembourg, Cayman, Delaware for tax efficiency; (2) Acquisition entity: LLC vs. corporation vs. partnership; (3) Interest deductibility: maximise legal interest deduction on acquisition debt; (4) Tax losses: carry forward opportunities from target; (5) Jurisdiction: choose tax-efficient structure; (6) Step-up: asset purchase vs. stock purchase treatment; (7) Post-transaction: tax-efficient operating structure. Considerations: (1) Tax efficiency vs. complexity; (2) Compliance costs; (3) LP tax-ability (tax-exempt vs. taxable); (4) Regulatory approval if cross-border; (5) Operational efficiency vs. tax optimization. Tax DD: (1) Comprehensive tax specialist engagement; (2) Model tax efficiency of different structures; (3) Pre-clearance with tax authorities if needed; (4) Document rationale for structures; (5) Ongoing tax management plan. Sophisticated PE firms invest significantly in tax optimization — can meaningfully enhance returns without operational changes.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD produces a ''pro-forma'' income statement. What is the purpose?', '["Random reconstruction","Purpose: (1) Show target ''as if'' acquired at beginning of period; (2) Incorporate normalised operations; (3) Include expected synergies or adjustments; (4) Support valuation based on forward view; (5) Compare consistently across scenarios; (6) LBO model foundation; bridge from current to future state","Only history","Random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pro-forma income statement purpose: (1) Shows business ''as if'' PE had owned from start of period; (2) Normalises: removes non-recurring items, owner-specific expenses; (3) Adjusts for acquisition effects: interest on new debt, amortisation of intangibles, management changes; (4) Supports: (a) Valuation analysis (what does acquired business look like?); (b) LBO model (base for projections); (c) Banker presentations; (d) IC decisions; (e) LP communication. Typical adjustments: (1) Remove non-recurring items; (2) Normalise owner salary; (3) Adjust interest expense for new capital structure; (4) Add intangible amortisation from step-up; (5) Reflect standalone costs if carve-out; (6) Include expected synergies (if applicable). Pro-forma vs. adjusted EBITDA: (1) Pro-forma shows fuller P&L perspective; (2) Adjusted EBITDA shows earnings base. Both important for PE analysis — complementary views.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD identifies ''contingent consideration'' on the target. Examples include:', '["Random","Contingent items: (1) Earnouts from prior acquisitions; (2) Performance-based bonuses; (3) Deferred compensation; (4) Contingent tax payments; (5) Legal settlement contingencies; (6) Regulatory approvals; (7) Milestone-based payments; (8) Escrow claims","Only taxes","Only cash"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Contingent consideration types: (1) Earnouts: contingent payments from prior acquisitions based on target achievement; (2) Performance bonuses: employee incentives conditional on metrics; (3) Deferred compensation: future payouts based on tenure, performance; (4) Contingent tax: uncertain tax positions (UTPs); (5) Legal settlements: potential payments pending; (6) Regulatory: compliance costs contingent on rulings; (7) Milestones: acquisition earnouts, joint venture payments; (8) Escrow: funds held pending resolution. Treatment: (1) Quantify probability-adjusted expected value; (2) Include in debt-like items for EV bridge; (3) SPA representations; (4) Seller indemnities. Analysis: (1) Contract terms and conditions; (2) Achievement probability; (3) Timing expectations; (4) Likely amounts; (5) Risk factors. Proper FDD: (1) Identifies all contingent items; (2) Quantifies expected value; (3) Negotiates treatment; (4) Clarifies post-closing responsibility.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD evaluates the target''s ''recurring revenue'' quality. What distinguishes high-quality recurring revenue?', '["Any recurring","Quality factors: (1) Long-term contracts (5+ years); (2) High renewal rates (95%+); (3) Contract escalators; (4) Customer diversification within base; (5) Service quality driving retention; (6) Switching costs; (7) Strategic importance to customers; (8) Payment terms (upfront, multi-year)","Only subscriber count","Only revenue"]'::jsonb, 1, 'High-quality recurring revenue criteria: (1) Duration: long-term contracts (5+ years) vs. month-to-month; (2) Retention: 95%+ gross retention; (3) Escalators: annual pricing increases built in; (4) Diversification: broad customer base within recurring segment; (5) Service quality: drives retention; (6) Switching costs: integration creates lock-in; (7) Strategic importance: customer''s business depends on service; (8) Payment: upfront vs. monthly billing; (9) Pricing power: ability to raise prices without losing customers. Types of recurring revenue: (1) Subscription (SaaS, licenses); (2) Maintenance contracts; (3) Long-term service contracts; (4) Retainer arrangements; (5) Partnership agreements; (6) Dealer/franchise fees. Valuation implications: (1) High-quality recurring: premium multiples (12-20x+); (2) Low-quality recurring: standard multiples; (3) Non-recurring: discount to blended multiples. For PE: (1) Recurring revenue anchors LBO thesis; (2) Validate retention, not just contract terms; (3) Track indicators over hold period.'),
  ('84f9bd80-690c-4b2e-845f-bac3459e09c7', 'due-diligence-financial', 'A PE firm''s FDD analyses ''M&A history'' of the target. What questions arise from historical acquisitions?', '["Random","Key questions: (1) Integration success rate; (2) Synergies realized vs. projected; (3) Purchase prices vs. current values; (4) Organisational impact; (5) Pending earnouts; (6) Related party conflicts; (7) Integration debt; (8) Future M&A capacity","Only prices","Only count"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Historical M&A analysis: (1) Integration success: were acquired businesses successfully integrated?; (2) Synergy realisation: planned synergies actually achieved?; (3) Purchase prices vs. values: were deals at appropriate prices?; (4) Organisational impact: cultural integration, retention; (5) Pending earnouts: obligations from prior deals; (6) Related party conflicts: deals with affiliated entities; (7) Integration debt: cost overruns, transition issues; (8) Future M&A capacity: organisational capability. Analysis framework: (1) Review each major acquisition: rationale, terms, outcome; (2) Assess integration patterns; (3) Measure synergy capture against projections; (4) Evaluate overall acquisition discipline; (5) Quantify financial impact. PE implications: (1) Strong M&A track record: platform potential, bolt-on capability; (2) Weak M&A: concerns about capability, past problems; (3) Pending issues: must address in SPA. Sophisticated FDD reviews 5-10 year M&A history to understand target''s capabilities and legacies.')
